summary.seg: This manuscript is a copy of Three Gospels and Acts. The Gospels of Matthew, Mark, and Luke are preceded by introductory texts containing the lives of the Evangelists. One of these, the life of Matthew, is an extract from the Greek translation by Sophronios of Jerome's work De viris illustribus.

The manuscript was copied in the first half of the 16th century by a scribe, Paschasios, who signed the copy presenting himself as ἀδελφός, 'brother'; therefore, he probably was a monk. Moreover, he probably was not a native Greek, as suggested by various elements. His script shows a certain hesitancy in the tracing of the forms, and it is very rigid, a typical characteristic of the script of non-proficient scribes. Moreover, interestingly, after the New Testament texts, Paschasios wrote a list of abbreviation in Greek script with their corresponding expanded forms, a Greek alphabet with phonetical transcriptions in Latin script, and an index of terms and expressions found in the preceding text, to which he refers, with notes in Latin.

support.material:
ff. 3-182 Western paper, folded in octavo. Some watermarks are visible: ff. 15-38, 79-86, 95-134 Pitcher surmounted by a a crown and a quatrefoil ( ca. 50 ca. 15 ), in the upper part of the leaf, near the edge, comparable to the type Briquet Pot 12618-12632 , dated between 1483 and 1545.
ff. 47-54, 135-142 Gothic letter P with upright bifid in the lower part, surmounted by a quatrefoil (or a cross) ( ca. 60 ca. 15 ), in the upper part of the leaf, near the edge, comparable to Briquet Lettre P 8643-8644 , which are dated in 1539-1531 and 1533-1534.
ff. 151-172 Shield containing a crown and lilies, surmounted by a quatrefoil; below letter C ( ca. 75 ca. 30 ), in the upper part of the leaf, near the edge, no similar parallels found in the main repertoires.
ff. 173-180 Shield containing a crown and lilies, surmounted by a quatrefoil; below letter d/b ( ca. 85 40 ), in the upper part of the leaf, near the edge, no similar parallels found in the main repertoires.

foliation.p: Modern pencil foliation, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin, right, from 3 to 182; two unnumbered parchment endleaves, one at the beginning, one at the end of the manuscript: [i] + 3-182 + [ii]. Folio numbers 1-2 assigned to leaves no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practice at Cambridge University Library).

From f. 7r, throughout the manuscript, in the upper margins, there are running titles written in red ink by the scribe, comprising the title of the work and, on the recto of the leaves, right, a folio number in Greek numerals, from α΄ (1, f. 7r), to ρξϛ΄ (166, f. 172r).

collation.p: The codex is formed mostly of quaternions. The first quire is a ternion from which the first two leaves have been excised, without loss of text.

signatures.p: Throughout the manuscript, the first leaf of the second part of each quire is signalled by a cross traced in black ink or in pencil in the lower margin, right, recto, see the first on f. 11r (the one on f. 4r seems different from the others, could it be a later addition?), the last on f. 177r. There are moreover two series of signatures.

The first is in Greek numerals (the number ζ΄, 7, is not present, but no quire is missing), written in brown ink or in pencil (these could be later additions), in the lower margin of the first leaf, recto, of the quires; in ink are written
β 1, β 2, β 3 ( ff. 15r-17r)
δ΄ ( f. 31r)
ε΄, ε 2 (ff. f. 39r and 41r)
ϛ΄ ( f. 47r). The remaining signatures, from η΄ ( f. 55r) to ο΄ ( f. 119r) are written in pencil.

Moreover, there is a series of signatures, written in brown ink by the scribe, in Arabic numerals, from 1 ( f. 127r) to 6 ( f. 167r), in the lower margin, right, of the first leaf recto of the quires.

collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords by the scribe, in brown ink, in the lower margin, right, directly under the text, on the verso of each leaf, passim also on the recto.

supportDesc.condition: The codex is in poor condition. There are tears on ff. 79, 86 (repaired along the edges with Japanese paper), and 98 (here with loss of text). The binding is damaged (see Binding), particularly the spine.

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 5r-172v A single column of 25-27 lines. ca. 120-125 ca. 80-90

handNote.p:
ff. 5r-174v, 178v-180v Hand A: the texts were all written in a minuscule Gebrauchsschrift, upright, by a non-Greek; some forms are hesitantly and almost clumsily traced. Breathings and accents are often absent. On f. 172v the scribe signed his copy as 'brother' Paschasios Paschasios
(Πασχάσιος, RGK I, 340).
The text is written in a light brown ink; titles, initials, and running titles in red.

decoDesc.decoNote: Thick initials in red ink throughout; they are bigger at the beginning of the texts, see e.g. ff. 7r, 50v.

additions.p: On f. 3r there are a few modern notes in pencil.
On f. 3v is pasted a label of Cambridge University Library.
In the lower margin of f. 5r is written, in ink, the shelfmark, Add. 4173.

binding.p:
Early modern western binding. Full limp leather cover over boards formed by folded paper leaves with manuscript text in Latin. Blind tooling on both boards: a geometrical pattern of triple and double fillets, with a central rectangle filled with rhombuses. On the spine (the fragment is preserved in the manuscript's enclosure), in black ink, Novum Testamentum Graece MSS. On the part of this label which remains on the left cover, can be read a handwritten note, unclear, Ven (?) 1550.
150 105 ca. 30
binding.condition: The manuscript is preserved in a box made by Wilson and Son. The left outer joint is completely split, the right outer joint is partially split. Part of the spine is lost, some remnants are kept within the enclosure.

accMat.p: Two parchment leaves have been used as endleaves, ff. [i], and [ii]. They derive from a Latin manuscript of the 13th century containing Canon Law with gloss (see Kerr).
Paper leaves in the cover, used as boards, come from a Latin paper manuscript, probably datable in the 15th century (see Kerr).
With the manuscript is preserved a detached fragment from the spine.

origin.p: The manuscript was copied by a scribe who signed the copy as brother Paschasios (see Colophon on f. 172v) in the first half of the 16th century. The two watermarks of the manuscript for which it was possible to find parallels in the repertoires confirm a date in the first half of the 16th century. The date of 1550 written on the left cover could be an indication for a more precise dating of the production of the manuscript, but the relation with the codex itself is not clear. More useful is the date of 1565, which has been written by the scribe on f. 173v, at the conclusion of a list of Greek script abbreviations: it can be assumed as terminus ante quem for the copy of the manuscript.

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by T. Swinburne Swinburne, T. ; his name is written on f. 3r.

history.acquisition: It was donated to the Library in 1905 by Reverend Charles Watson Watson, Charles , whose bookplate is pasted on f. 4r (see Easterling (1962), p. 304).

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on P. Easterling, 'Hand-list of the additional Greek manuscripts in the University Library, Cambridge', in Scriptorium 16 (1962), 302-323 (p. 304), and on an umpublished description by the librarian R.V. Kerr, kept in Cambridge University Library.
